      "thinking": {
        "text": "\nGood, I have data from both the retention_cohort tool and channel_financial tool. Let me analyze what I found:\n\nFrom retention_cohort data (Q4 2025 acquisition):\n- APP135 promo users: 1,396 guests acquired with 89.3% 30-day retention rate\n- Non-APP135 promo users: 1,003 guests acquired with 85.2% 30-day retention rate  \n- Other/null promo: 4,715 guests acquired with 85.9% retention\n- APP135 had avg first order of $19.17, second order of $19.62\n- Non-APP135 had avg first order of $21.82, second order of $21.91\n\nFrom channel_financial data (Q4 2025 transactions):\n- APP channel: 172,625 transactions, $21.78 avg order value, $3.76M total revenue\n- Other channels combined: 449,549 transactions\n  - In-Store: 125,001 transactions, $21.74 avg\n  - Kiosk: 94,301 transactions, $21.71 avg\n  - UberEats: 85,758 transactions, $21.74 avg\n  - DoorDash: 67,549 transactions, $21.85 avg\n  - GrubHub: 53,875 transactions, $21.83 avg\n  - Web: 23,065 transactions, $21.90 avg\n\nKey insights:\n1. The APP135 promo drove 4.1 percentage points higher retention (89.3% vs 85.2%)\n2. APP channel had 172,625 transactions in Q4 with $21.78 average check\n3. The promo acquired 1,396 new guests in Q4 with a very strong 89.3% return rate\n4. APP orders had slightly higher AOV ($21.78) than most other channels\n\nI should present this in a strategic executive summary format with the key business impact upfront, then supporting data.\n"
